turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail in Iowa included two identical Scooby vans, one of which had blue and white plates, presumably for decoy purposes. The vans are mechanically identical and have deep-tinted windows and raised roofs. The Secret Service often employs decoys to mix up travel plans and confuse potential attackers. The vans arrived and left together in a seven-car motorcade with four black Suburbans and a white minivan. Clinton is under constant protection by the Secret Service due to her front-runner status in the presidential race.

A Georgia mother of six has appealed for help after a fire destroyed her rented condo, leaving her family without anything. She is struggling to find a new permanent home while being unemployed and has been turned away by shelters that can only accommodate a few of her children. She has started a GoFundMe page to raise funds and is currently staying with a friend, far from her children's schools.

An Australian couple who entered into a surrogacy agreement in India were aware that the twin boys may be left stateless, newly uncovered documents reveal. The couple, from New South Wales, travelled to India in late 2012 and sought citizenship for a baby girl, but told consular staff they would be leaving her twin brother behind because they could not afford him. Despite being informed of the potential consequences, the couple went ahead with the arrangement and returned to Australia with the girl while leaving her brother behind. Consular staff expressed concerns that money had changed hands and if true, it would constitute child trafficking. The Indian case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case, where the Australian parents only brought back the twin sister.

Kecil, a one-year-old baby orangutan, had a tough start to life after being rejected by his natural mother and a surrogate mother. However, he found love with second surrogate mother Maggie at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo and the two have formed an inseparable bond. Maggie, who has already raised four children and a fifth surrogate, has proven herself as a great parent once again. Kecil and Maggie will be on display for the first time this weekend and will eventually become part of an exhibit featuring the zoo's other orangutans.

Javier Pastore has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the best footballer in the world, stating that he believes Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's win against Nice on Saturday and they face Barcelona in the second leg of their Champions League tie on Tuesday. They need to overturn a 3-1 deficit to advance to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, has successfully campaigned to change NICE guidelines on when to clamp the umbilical cord after birth, after discovering that clamping it within seconds of delivery was not backed by evidence. The new guidelines state that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord "earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby", and it can be clamped within five minutes, but left longer if the mother requests. This change will allow mothers to hold their babies while still attached to them, and will also reduce the risk of iron deficiency anaemia. The campaign faced resistance from some doctors and midwives, who questioned why Burleigh was challenging medical protocol.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to show no mercy if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children in exchange for food. Fourteen soldiers are accused of abusing children as young as nine as they begged for something to eat. The French defence ministry has denied covering up the scandal and launched an investigation when it received a leaked UN report on the subject in July last year. A UN employee accused of leaking the report has been suspended. The violence in the Central African Republic has pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels who led a coup in 2013.

A shocking video shows a Texas pastor's wife, Aracely Meza, attempting to resurrect a two-year-old boy who had died two months earlier. The child's mother had reportedly told people he was possessed by demons. Meza was charged with injury to a child by omission after the police found out about the incident through an anonymous tip. Neighbors say the pastors presided over church services at the home and that children were living there. Meza's husband, also a pastor, was not charged.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, both from Scotland, have progressed to the second round of the Betfred World Championship. Higgins, a four-time champion, defeated Robert Milkins 10-5, while Dott ousted Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins is playing well and has expressed his desire to win the title and become a five-time champion, while Dott is a proven Crucible class act who has won the title before.

Barcelona players Neymar, Dani Alves and Adriano celebrated a La Liga victory over Celta Vigo, but their choice of matching denim was questionable. The players appear to have enjoyed the game despite the team's poor performance, with center-back Jeremy Mathieu scoring the winning goal after 73 minutes. Brazilian defender Dani Alves admitted that the team struggled after the international break, but praised his fellow players for their impressive defensive display.

Jose Mourinho, the coach of Chelsea, is planning to sign Koke, a midfielder from Atletico Madrid. The club's technical director, Michael Emenalo, watched Koke during a recent match, and Mourinho is reportedly considering using second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as a makeweight in the deal. Koke is valued at around £50 million, but Mourinho may be willing to pay that to strengthen Chelsea's midfield.

Tom Ballard, the son of late climber Alison Hargreaves, plans to climb K2, 20 years after his mother died descending from its peak. He aims to follow in his mother's footsteps, though he realizes that he climbs for himself. Alison Hargreaves was a revered figure in the climbing world and the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. He was only six years old when his mother died on her way down from the summit of K2. K2 is considered more difficult to reach than the summit of Mount Everest, with dozens dying during attempts to reach the top.

A consortium of companies has claimed to have discovered up to 100 billion barrels of oil worth trillions of pounds in the Weald Basin in southern England. UK Oil & Gas Investments says it has discovered the reserves at a site near Gatwick Airport and estimates that the area could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. However, industry experts remain sceptical of the claims and have warned that only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction. Fracking could be required to retrieve significant volumes, they said. The British Geological Survey estimated the basin held just 4.4 billion barrels of shale oil. The Government owns the land under residents' houses, meaning they have no right to any oil found beneath them. Residents may receive compensation if firms undertake fracking in their area. The Government gains money from tax on oil extracted.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in pilot culls and now advocates trapping the badgers in cages and then shooting them. The BVA notes that the effectiveness and humaneness of free-running badger shooting has not been demonstrated conclusively after two years of culling. The BVA still supports the overall goal of badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. However, animal welfare campaigners criticize the BVA's continued support for cage-trapping and shooting. Environment Secretary Liz Truss has announced plans by a future Conservative government to roll out more culls across the country. Despite controversy, Ms Truss urges politicians not to make the cull a party political issue.

It is claimed that modern technology creates more pitfalls in relationships, and activities like checking social media on a date or taking food photos can be negative. To avoid embarrassment and show yourself in a better light, it is suggested to keep phones off the dining table, avoid taking photos for Instagram, not changing your relationship status too quickly, and avoid bragging about dating app interactions. Other tips include refraining from using location services, calling if the date goes well, keeping a taxi app handy, and using Snapchat for updates. It is also suggested to not assume your date will find everything funny, and not to record them with Google Glass.It

Tottenham Hotspur will face Aston Villa in a Premier League match at White Hart Lane on Saturday, March 28th. Tottenham will be without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris due to injuries while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt. On the other hand, Aston Villa boss Tim Sherwood will be without Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, and Carles Gil, but Aly Cissokho could return. In head-to-head league record, Tottenham has won 60 times, drawn 34 times, and Aston Villa has won 49 times. Tottenham has won the last five PL meetings with Aston Villa, and Aston Villa has scored just six goals in their last 12 Premier League matches against Tottenham. Tottenham has gained 10 points from losing positions at home this season, more than any other side, and Aston Villa has gained no points from losing positions away from home in the Premier League this season.

A mother who made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby at just 20 weeks had her wedding dress redesigned so her tiny daughter could be buried in it. Jaye Cox and her husband, Matthew, decided to deliver their daughter Annabelle prematurely on May 5 last year after scans showed she had developed a serious form of Spina Bifida. Annabelle was born weighing just 290 grams at Canberra Hospital and her distraught parents were able to cradle her in the short five minutes she survived. Jaye and Matthew Cox delivered their daughter Annabelle at just 20 weeks in Canberra Hospital after scans showed she had developed a serious form of Spina Bifida. The couple contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization, to help them create a dress from Jaye's wedding gown to bury Annabelle in. Annabelle was born with a very faint heartbeat, and her parents and siblings were able to hold her in the short time she survived. Angel Gowns picked up Jaye's wedding dress and returned the redesigned version for Annabelle on the day she was going to be born. Angel Gowns is dedicated to turning donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. The family, including her two older sisters, were able to take photos with Annabelle in her gown before the funeral. Angel Gowns created a replica dress for the family to have in their house, and Ms Cox looks at it every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns donates outfits to more than 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and deals directly with families like the Cox's and different children charities. To donate your wedding dress or volunteer with Angel Gowns, visit [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A police constable named Ronnie Lungu, who is black, has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police. The employment tribunal ruled that the force had unlawfully discriminated against Mr. Lungu on grounds of race, after he was not promoted due to the colour of his skin, his internal assessments were secretly downgraded, and derogatory comments were made about him based on his race, violating his dignity. Wiltshire Police has denied the claims but has been found to have singled out Mr. Lungu as a 'marked man' on grounds of his race. Mr. Lungu still serves as a PC with the force but wants reassurance that the force will take discrimination seriously and implement new procedures to tackle discrimination.

A parent named KentuckyFriedIdiot taught his newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle by demonstrating the trick himself. The video has been viewed over 190,000 times and has received positive comments about how cute and smart the daughter is.

A set of rare photographs taken in the dawn of photography is expected to fetch up to £30,000 at an auction in Cirencester tomorrow. The images, captured between 1850 and 1855 by photographer Hugh Owen, depict the city of Bristol, including the city centre, St Mary Redcliffe church, and The Fourteen Stars Tavern building. Many of the buildings pictured have changed dramatically over the years, particularly the High Street area, while some have remained almost unchanged, such as the view through St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist. The albumen prints were made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s. The photos provide a unique glimpse into the past of Bristol, which was almost completely destroyed in World War II.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter, who forced Liam Fox to resign as Defence Secretary, is attempting to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate Tom Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. Boulter is using £30,000 of his funds to campaign against Tugendhat, whom he considers to be a vendetta target, as Tugendhat's father, Sir Michael Tugendhat, awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages after Boulter made libellous remarks about Fox on Sky TV.

A six-year-old Aston Villa fan named Charlie Pye applied for the job of Villa manager after the sacking of Paul Lambert. He received a letter from new manager Tim Sherwood congratulating him on his knowledge of the game and offering him a win bonus of a chocolate bar and other goodies. Although Charlie missed out on the job, Sherwood kept the letter on file and sent a special message to the young fan after guiding Villa to the FA Cup semi-finals. Charlie is the captain of Norton Lindsey and has appointed his parents as assistant managers in his dream team.

Atletico Madrid defeated Cordoba 2-0 with goals from Antoine Griezmann and Saul Niguez, putting them ahead of Valencia in the race for the third Champions League spot. Valencia have a chance to reclaim third place with a win against Villarreal on Sunday. Atletico is also closing in on second-placed Real Madrid, who are four points behind leaders Barcelona. Sevilla maintained their unbeaten home record with a 2-0 win against Athletic Bilbao.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one named Abby Swinfield died after a house party where she suffered two heart attacks and died of multiple organ failure due to taking M-Cat (Mephedrone). Her cousin claims she didn't take the drug voluntarily, suggesting her drink was spiked. Her mother is devastated, and her three-year-old son now has no mother. The police have arrested a 20-year-old girl for supplying Class B drugs and have released her on bail.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, which has raised concerns for the health of children in the area. The radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour were detected underneath a slide, which is nearly half the recommended annual limit of exposure for a person. The reason behind the radiation levels is not yet clear, but authorities believe it could be coming from something buried underneath the park. The park has been fenced off, and the city has set up a health advice office to answer queries from concerned parents. Radiation levels in Japan have heightened concerns since the 2011 Fukushima disaster.

Amir Khan believes that Kell Brook has called him out in order to earn a big payday, as Brook has not faced any significant opponents in his career. Khan has announced a fight with Chris Algieri next month, but has since backtracked, claiming that there are "some more options on the table." Khan claims that Brook is not a big name in the UK or in the US, and is not able to face the world's biggest names. Khan insists that he is not avoiding Brook, but Brook needs Khan to make that big money.

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunning modern three-bedroom home, named 'PV14', which boasts a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, and a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and the city's downtown. The home's walls are made of sheet rock, but the ceilings are left exposed and the shipping container gates are unpainted. The designers wanted people to know what they were standing in when they stepped into the home. Columns had to be placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials, and spray foam was used between the building layers to provide insulation. The two-story, glass-paneled tower reflects the shape of the long, slim pool. Deep porches protect the home from direct sunlight while still allowing natural light to seep in, and the upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors. The couple found the perfect spot - on one of the highest elevations in the city, offering one of the best views. After more than two years of design and construction, the couple are finally preparing to move into their new home.

Jordan Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool this week, keeping him at Anfield until 2020. The 19-year-old winger made a notable impact in his eight appearances for the club since returning from a loan spell at Derby County in January. Liverpool are also expected to announce new contracts for Jordan Henderson and Martin Skrtel this week, while talks are ongoing with defender Jon Flanagan.

Rik Mayall, the comedian known for his role as Alan B'Stard in The New Statesman, has died suddenly at age 56. He had no will, and this could result in a large inheritance tax bill for his family, who stand to inherit his £1.2 million estate. Under UK law, his wife and children would be entitled to a portion of the estate, with the exact amount depending on the chattels and personal property included in the net estate. Andrew Kidd, a specialist probate solicitor, suggests that Mayall's family could avoid inheritance tax by drawing up a deed of variation. Mayall's writing partner Laurence Marks played a role in getting David Cameron into Downing Street, and he has remained friends with Cameron, who sent the pair a handwritten letter thanking them for their support.

The situation in Yemen's capital, Sanaa, is chaotic due to fighting between the Houthi rebels and the Saudi-led coalition. Countries are trying to evacuate their citizens during a small window when Saudi planes are not bombing the city. Air India is helping evacuate Indian nationals and other people working in other nations. The evacuees are flown to Djibouti and then to their home countries. Passengers on the Air India flight included people from Yemen, India, and other countries who have been living in Sanaa. The scene of people scrambling onto the airport tarmac with luggage shows the stress of living in a war zone. Some passengers are exhausted and jangled by the shelling and lack of electricity. Despite the challenges, the Air India crew offered drinks to the passengers as if they were on a vacation flight.

An Italian priest has been sacked after allegations emerged that he participated in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The priest, who was a member of a religious order in Taranto, was dismissed following an online lover contacting the church authorities with a dossier containing evidence of sex with prostitutes, role-play, and explicit gay web chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios in which his lover played the disciple Judas Escariot, and had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. The diocese confirmed the priest's dismissal but stated there were no other prelates involved. The scandal is just the latest to engulf the Vatican, with the priest allegedly attempting to seduce his unemployed laborer lover after revealing his homosexuality during online chats.

A recent study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccine and autism, even among high risk children with older siblings diagnosed with autism. This is consistent with numerous other studies over the last 15 years, which have found no connection between vaccines and autism. Despite this, many parents continue to associate vaccines with autism, and vaccination rates among children with older siblings with autism are lower than those without. The study found that vaccination rates were 92% for children without autistic siblings and 86% for those with an affected sibling. The study's lead author, Anjali Jain, concludes that 'the only conclusion that can be drawn from the study is that there is no signal to suggest a relationship between MMR and the development of autism in children with or without a sibling who has autism'. The editorial accompanying the study confirms that 'taken together, some dozen studies have now shown that the age of onset of ASD does not differ between vaccinated and unvaccinated children, the severity or course of ASD does not differ between vaccinated and unvaccinated children, and now the risk of ASD recurrence in families does not differ between vaccinated and unvaccinated children.'

A new report by Human Rights Watch has found that ISIS is kidnapping and raping women and children, including Yazidi girls as young as eight, in Iraq. The report details the suffering of 20 women and girls who were able to escape from ISIS and shows a system of organized rape and sexual assault, sexual slavery and forced marriage, acts that constitute war crimes. Victims reported being sold as "property" and forced to marry their captors. The report also highlights the trauma faced by the women and girls who have escaped and the need for better support and treatment for them.

A shooting at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina left one person dead on Monday morning. Kenneth Stancil, a former student who did not graduate from the college, is believed to have entered the library and fired one shot, killing employee Rodney Lane. Stancil is considered armed and dangerous and police are searching for him. Classes have been cancelled for the rest of the day and students have been evacuated from the campus. A motive for the shooting is not yet known.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council could be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to "negative publicity" from the grooming scandal. The council will offer up to £200,000 to candidates instead of the previous salary of £160,000. The rest of the cabinet resigned earlier this year after a Government report found that the council was "not fit for purpose" and "in denial" about exploitation in the area. HR chief Phil Howe suggested offering additional incentives to attract candidates, but Councillor Caven Vines, leader of the Ukip group, expressed discomfort with the idea.

Cesc Fabregas broke his nose during Chelsea's match against Stoke City and will wear a protective face mask for the team's upcoming matches. The mask was made by the Ortholabsport in Milan and features Fabregas's initial and squad number. The center is known for its work with former Chelsea players, including Fernando Torres and Demba Ba, as well as the Italian national team. Fabregas travelled to Milan to have the mask fitted and could be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday, while Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks with hamstring trouble.

Andros Townsend, a Tottenham Hotspur winger, scored an equalizer for England in their 1-1 friendly draw with Italy in Turin on Tuesday night. He says that criticism from commentators like Paul Merson provided motivation for him, which he used to silence his detractors with his successful strike.

A man named Joseph O'Riordan has been accused of trying to murder his cheating wife, Amanda. O'Riordan stabbed his wife eight times after discovering she had been having an affair with a postman. He has pleaded not guilty to attempted murder. During his trial, it was revealed that he wrote a letter from prison asking his wife to send him a suit for the trial. In the letter, he also mentioned needing a 'decent jumper' and his 'beige casual jacket', as well as his 'blue suit' and 'three ties that will go with the suit'. His wife sobbed in court as the letter was read out and also admitted that she had an affair but didn't want to hurt him.

The UK will open its first three proton beam therapy centres in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017, following the successful treatment of cancer-stricken five-year-old Ashya King with proton beam therapy in Prague. Proton Partners International Ltd will operate the centres, which will available to NHS cancer patients. The announcement comes after Ashya's parents, Brett and Naghmeh King, sparked an international manhunt last year after taking their son out of hospital in Southampton without doctors' consent to access proton beam therapy. Professor Sir Chris Evans and UK life sciences and healthcare investors have committed almost £100 million equity finance into the company. Ashya's successful recovery from brain cancer has prompted the establishing of the proton beam therapy centres in the UK.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are recruiting paramedics from Australia because it is cheaper than training them in Britain. They are offering a "golden hello" payment of £4,500 and a salary of £30,200 to attract applicants. The selection process, held at five-star hotels, takes only a few hours and involves a practical demonstration on dummies, written exam, and interview. The London Ambulance Service has hired 225 paramedics from Australia and 175 from New Zealand in the last few months. The cost of training one paramedic in Britain is £50,000, but it only costs £90,000 to send a delegation to Australia for recruitment. However, this solution is only a temporary one because the ambulance service is severely understaffed and needs to train more paramedics in the UK. Some paramedics are leaving the NHS because they are frustrated with the long waits at A&E units and the increase in non-urgent calls.

Chelsea have turned to the latest fitness technology to help them win the Premier League title, partnering with leading wellness solutions provider Technogym to kit out their Cobham training ground with state-of-the-art equipment. The Stamford Bridge club has seven points clear with a game in hand over their closest rivals and seven games remaining, and players such as Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured working out. Technogym's founder and President Nerio Alessandri said the company is proud to be selected as Chelsea's fitness equipment partner and will work closely with the players to help them achieve the best performance possible. Meanwhile, Chelsea have had two players nominated for the PFA Player of the Year awards, while Hazard is hot favourite to pick up the award for his inspiring displays.

It is a well-known fact that language development is an important aspect of childhood growth, but recent studies have revealed that babies are capable of much more than just speaking. Research conducted at the University of Missouri found that 11-month-olds are capable of understanding complex social situations, such as bullying, friendship, and being a bystander. The study showed that when babies were shown a ball disappearing through a wall and then given the ball to play with, they attempted to work out its secret by banging it on a table. Even more surprising, after seeing a magic trick where a ball appeared to go through a solid wall, they repeated the trick by trying to drop a toy car through the wall.

These findings are fascinating because they suggest that babies have a natural curiosity and desire to learn, even from seemingly impossible situations. Surprisingly, the babies in the study were more interested in playing with the ball than a brand new toy they had never seen before. This highlights the idea that babies learn best when they are surprised, and it suggests that they use their existing knowledge to form predictions, and when those predictions are shown to be wrong, they use it as an opportunity to learn more. "When babies are surprised, they learn much better, as though they are taking the occasion to try to figure something out about their world," says Lisa Feigerson, a professor at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore.

Furthermore, research has shown that babies are born with innate knowledge of math and physics, including the understanding that objects cannot pass through solid walls. Aimee Stahl, the lead author of the study, believes that young babies are "remarkably sophisticated thinkers" and that they use their core knowledge to empower new learning. These findings demonstrate that babies are not just passive learners, but active thinkers who use their curiosity to understand the world around them.

Manny Pacquiao trained for his upcoming fight against Floyd Mayweather on the streets of Los Angeles, where he worked on his fitness and stamina. He ran with his dog Pacman around Griffith Park and showed off his skills by shadow boxing. Pacquiao also worked on his core strength during a training session on the mats.

A cat who had been stuck in a hole in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years has been freed. The cat, named Biso, was trapped behind the wall at the Mohamed Naguib metro station and survived thanks to an elderly man who fed him scraps of food every day. The cat's plight came to the attention of animal activists after a picture of its tail was posted on Facebook. The rescue mission took more than five hours, and the terrified cat only emerged from the hole after one worker went inside to bring him out. Unfortunately, Biso then quickly ran away before anyone could catch him.

At least 35 workers were killed when a dairy factory in Yemen was hit by an airstrike during a Saudi-led bombing campaign against Shiite rebel positions in the country. The factory had previously been used as a rebel weapons cache, and the airstrikes flattened the warehouses but only partially destroyed the main factory building. International aid groups have expressed alarm over high civilian casualties in Yemen's escalating crisis, with UNICEF reporting that 62 children were killed and 30 wounded during fighting in the past week.

A truck collision on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks caused delays for hundreds of morning commuters in Boston. The truck crashed into a car on Interstate 93 southbound in the Dorchester neighborhood at 6am, and both drivers were taken to hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. Due to safety concerns, replacement shuttle buses were provided for southbound passengers, causing long queues. The incident caused headaches for locals trying to get to work and traffic remained backed up even after the truck was towed at 8:30am. The truck driver was a 57-year-old Woburn man, and the car driver was a 42-year-old Attleboro man, but no names were released.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised the performance of his young players in their latest European loss and stated that the club has no intention of overspending in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. Nigel Wray, the chairman of Saracens, had earlier suggested that the salary cap should be scrapped to allow the club to compete at the top level in Europe, but McCall stated that they will wait for the right player to improve their side without making unnecessary signings. McCall also highlighted the excitement of having a young pack of players who could be the mainstay of the club for the next four to five seasons.

The decomposing bodies of the accused terrorists responsible for killing 148 people at a Kenyan university were paraded in a primary school. The bodies were driven around the town before being parked at the primary school where hundreds gathered to view them. One of the survivors, Cynthia Cheroitich, who hid in a wardrobe for two days, described her ordeal. Four attackers died during the siege and their nationalities have not been revealed. Kenyan troops searching the building were alarmed when they heard sounds coming from inside a wardrobe. A survivor was initially too petrified to come out of the wardrobe, but police officers eventually convinced her that they were not al-Shabaab gunmen. Four suspects were detained, with one being a Tanzanian man. Al-Shabaab said more attacks like the university massacre were planned.T

Arsenal must act swiftly if they hope to sign Petr Cech this summer. The Chelsea goalkeeper, who is set to leave Stamford Bridge at the end of the season, is a long-term target for Arsenal, but they will face competition from other clubs for his signature. The Gunners must overcome several obstacles, including Chelsea's high valuation of Cech and the club's reluctance to sell to Premier League rivals. However, Cech is considering a move to the Emirates Stadium and hopes his service to Chelsea will allow him to make the final decision on his next destination.

Frankie Dettori will not be riding for Sheikh Joaan Al Thani in France this summer as the owner has signed up Gregory Benoist to ride his horses in that country. This decision was made due to the expansion of Sheikh Joaan's operation, which now includes 80 horses in France and almost 100 in Britain. Dettori will focus on the British flat season, but will still ride horses sent to France to race. Thierry Jarnet will continue to ride Treve for Sheikh Joaan. Charlie Hills-trained Acomb Stakes winner Connection put in a decent gallop under William Buick, who Hills hopes will ride his colt in the Classic. AP McCoy rode his last race at Cheltenham and will not ride again until Sandown's end-of-season meeting on Saturday.

Lois Lilienstein, one of the co-stars of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" has died at the age of 78. She died peacefully in Toronto after being diagnosed with a rare form of cancer in October 2021. She was a singer and joined Sharon Hampson and Bram Morrison to launch their singing trio in 1978. The TV show ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989 and continued in reruns on Nickelodeon until 1995. She left the trio in 2000.

French freediver Guillaume Néry jumped into Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas without scuba gear and holding his breath in a daring stunt captured in a video filmed by his girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier in 2010. The hole is 660 feet deep, and Néry doesn't go to the bottom, but the video is still impressive as he holds his breath for minutes on end. Freediving is a form of underwater diving where no scuba gear or breathing apparatus is used, and free divers go through sophisticated mind-body control techniques to push self-induced apnoea to the limits. Néry revealed a few years ago that he didn't really reach the bottom of the hole, but the video is still incredibly impressive.

A suicide bomber in Afghanistan affiliated with ISIS killed at least 33 people and injured more than 100 others near a bank in Jalalabad. The attack was claimed by an ISIS offshoot called ISIS Wilayat Khorasan. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack, condemning it and the use of suicide attacks in densely populated areas. The UN condemned the violence and expressed concerns about the growth of ISIS in the region.

Laura Wells, a plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched an eco-friendly swimwear line in collaboration with Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy. The collection features one and two-piece suits made entirely from 100 per cent recycled materials and is inspired by the ocean. The swimsuits come in sizes 10 through to 24 and feature designs such as plunging V-necks, criss-cross straps and high-waisted bottoms. Laura said the primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping prices affordable. The collection is available now.

TrackYourDose is a £1.49 iOS app developed by Germany-based esooka that records a user's personal radiation exposure, including exposure from changes in location and flights. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland, based on PTB's study of cosmic radiation at typical flight altitudes since 1997. The app calculates solar activity for the flight, and users input flight details and the current solar activity. It also accounts for gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground, as well as medical examinations with ionizing radiation. The measurement is called the "ambient dose equivalent" and is recorded in microsieverts (µSv). The annual radiation of a typical person in Europe is around 2,100 µSv, while the average annual radiation of a US citizen is around 3,000 μSv. Pilots are at risk of skin cancer due to cockpit radiation similar to tanning bed levels. The app offers a way for frequent flyers to track their exposure to radiation.

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility due to a listeria outbreak that is linked to the deaths of three people, according to an announcement made by the company on Friday. The decision was made as an "abundance of caution" to ensure the safety of its consumers. The recall earlier in March affected ten products made on a production line at the company's headquarters in Brenham, Texas.

Jon Hamm, star of Mad Men, has been exposed for his involvement in a college hazing scandal at the University of Texas at Austin in 1990. Court documents allege that Hamm, who was 20 at the time, and other fraternity members at Sigma Nu subjected a prospective pledge to two hours of brutal physical attacks, including being beaten with a paddle and set on fire, and then later hazed another potential pledge in the same way. Hamm was eventually charged with hazing and assault but the charges were dismissed before he began his successful acting career. The incident resulted in the closure of the Sigma Nu fraternity at UT-Austin.

The UK has pledged to protect the Falkland Islands from "Argentinian bullying" after the country launched legal action against British companies exploring for oil off the islands. The move follows a speech by Argentine President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner, which prompted the UK Foreign Office to summon her ambassador. The legal complaint listed three British and two US companies, accusing them of exploring for fossil fuels without permission. Argentina has warned the rig owner that it could face "legal consequences" over the drilling. The UK Foreign Secretary has stated that President Kirchner's threats are "illegal" and that the UK will protect the islanders from Argentine bullying as they develop their oil and gas industry.

Passengers on a Delta Air Lines flight experienced an anxious moment when their plane was met by firefighters wearing protective suits at LaGuardia Airport after a reported odor of smoke. Firefighters using a thermal imaging camera located a potential heat source and passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes while the situation was being investigated. The plane was taken out of service for an inspection and any necessary maintenance.

David Luiz injured his hamstring in a match against Marseille and will be out for at least four weeks. To pass the time, he got a new hairstyle, a man bun, which he posted on Instagram. His PSG teammate found it amusing and shared it on his own page. Although Luiz's hairstyle is a source of humor for some, his injury is not, as his team and manager will miss him in upcoming matches.

US President Barack Obama believes that diplomacy is the best way to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. Obama has stated that a comprehensive, long-term deal is the best option and that he will keep Congress apprised of the "substance of the deal" during the upcoming debate. Obama highlighted the rigorous inspections to which Tehran will be subject and stated that if Iran cheats, the world will know. The final deal has yet to be reached, but the outline text agreed to between Tehran and the P5+1 group is a major breakthrough in the 12-year international crisis over Iran's nuclear program. However, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and other critics have expressed strong opposition to the deal.

A 12-year-old girl named Rose McGrath, who has been battling Leukemia for two years, has been dismissed from her private Catholic school, St. Joseph's Middle School, due to her lack of attendance and poor academic performance. The school claims that they made many accommodations for Rose, but they were not enough to help her. Rose's mother says that her daughter is not skipping school to have fun, but because she is sick and struggling to attend classes and finish her schoolwork. Despite her illness, Rose wants to continue attending school and her family is fighting to have her re-enrolled. They believe that the accommodations made for Rose were inadequate for a child with such a serious diagnosis.

Passive smoking doesn't just affect humans, it also affects plants. Researchers in Germany found that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. This could explain why some plants and herbal teas contain high levels of nicotine, despite it being banned as an insecticide. The study also showed that cats and dogs exposed to tobacco smoke are more likely to develop certain types of cancer, and that nicotine concentration in plants decreases as time progresses. These findings highlight the transfer of chemical substances between plants and shed light on the success of farming practices such as crop rotation and co-cultivation of vegetables.

A video shows a battle between two chameleons for a female mate in Madagascar. The males vie for the attention of the female, and one is ultimately forced to retreat. The more aggressive chameleon bites and chases his rival out of the tree. The defeated chameleon struggles to escape but is pursued by the victorious one. The video ends with both chameleons climbing a tree branch.

Jack Cosgrove, a 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop, has agreed to join Edinburgh next season on a two-year deal. He has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side and has penned a deal tying him to the Murrayfield outfit until May 2017. Cosgrove, who is "over the moon" to be coming north, has a strong set-piece game and hopes to add something extra to the squad. He looks up to Alasdair Dickinson, an exceptional player in the same position, and hopes to learn from him.

Aaron Hernandez, the former New England Patriots player who was found guilty of murdering Odin Lloyd, has been moved to the maximum security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center near Shirley, Massachusetts. He is being held separately from other prisoners and is on suicide watch, and is now equipped with green prison scrubs and his tattoos are being examined for gang affiliations. Hernandez was previously using the drug "angel dust," a form of PCP, which can cause violent outbursts and paranoia, sources say. The NFL will now have to investigate how a drug-using sports star could have avoided rigorous testing.

Manchester City has indicated that young Academy players may be needed to fill gaps in the first-team squad, which could mean that defender Jason Denayer may return from his loan deal at Celtic next season. Theclub is committed to investing in 'homegrown' talent, and Denayer, who hails from Belgium, fits the category of young players who can be included in the first-team squad. Celtic is keen to retain Denayer's services, but the club's ambitions may be challenging to meet.

Ander Herrera, the Manchester United midfielder, wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons, following his successful spell at Athletic Bilbao. He wanted to keep using the name Ander Herrera from Athletic Bilbao, which he had during his good three years at the club. Herrera has had a stop-start beginning to life at Old Trafford but has forced his way into Louis van Gaal's starting line-up with a series of impressive displays that have coincided with the club's upturn in results. He took his tally to seven goals in all competitions with his double as United won 3-1 at home to Aston Villa in the Premier League on Saturday. The 25-year-old hopes to show a lot more emotion as United target silverware in the future.

Despite suffering a heavy defeat in the Champions League quarter-final against Bayern Munich, Porto supporters gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. The team bus was greeted with loud cheers and chanting from proud fans, with star striker Jackson Martinez and other players looking perplexed by the warm reception. The defeat was Porto's first in the tournament this season and ended their unbeaten run. Despite the loss, Porto coach Julen Lopetegui conceded that Bayern is one of the best teams in the world and the favorite to win the title.

The BBC has been criticized for creating an online computer game that simulates the dangerous journey Syrian refugees face as they try to flee their war-torn country. In the game, players make decisions about how to escape Syria and reach Europe, with often-grim outcomes such as being separated from family, sold to militia, or beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean. Middle East expert Chris Walker called the game "sickening," and Twitter users reacted furiously to the game, which came under fire for turning the suffering of millions into a "children's game." The BBC has defended the game, saying it shows the choices faced by thousands of Syrian families every day and has achieved a high number of online hits.

Boston marathon bomber Dzhokar Tsarnaev's two victims, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the attack, have appealed for him to be sentenced to life in prison without parole instead of the death penalty. The couple's statement comes after the Richards, the family of eight-year-old Martin Richard who was killed in the blast, made a similar appeal. Tsarnaev is facing the death penalty after being found guilty of all 30 charges related to the April 15, 2013 attack. The jury will make the final decision on his sentence.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Dr. Ayse Giray, who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement occurred before the judge was set to rule on Giray's claim to be retroactively named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company. The lawsuit was based on $500,000 that Giray's family reportedly lent Ulukaya to start Chobani. Chobani has faced further business problems, with a product recall and negative EBITDA, leading to private-equity firm TPG investing $750 million in the company, and the possibility of Ulukaya being replaced as CEO.

Diego Costa is expected to miss Chelsea's games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United, but is likely to return for the clash against Arsenal on April 26. He has a hamstring injury, and will focus on strength sessions and intensive massages before seeing a specialist. Dependent on the final outcome of the title race, Chelsea may give Costa an extended break between now and the end of the season to help him overcome his hamstring problems. Loic Remy will lead the line in Chelsea's game against QPR.

The England C team, which is made up of non-league players aged 23 and under, is facing the axe as part of the Football Association's spending review. The FA hopes to save £30million to fund the improvement of grassroots football. The team's manager, Paul Fairclough, has selected players such as Craig Mackail-Smith and George Boyd, who went on to play at full international level, although not for England. The team's future is uncertain, as there are no planned future fixtures and fears have increased about their long-term future. Former players include Steve Guppy, who won one senior England cap after playing once for his country at non-league level.

James Haskell, who plays for the London Wasps rugby team and the England national rugby team, dressed up as Iron Man, a character in the new movie Avengers: Age of Ultron, in an Instagram post. Haskell is a fan of the movie and the character and wanted to show his support by dressing up. The photo was accompanied by the message "Avengers movie is out so thought i would release the inner Iron Man", and was posted on his UnderArmorUK page. Haskell is a highly experienced and accomplished rugby player, having played for several clubs and teams around the world, including the London Wasps, Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders. Since returning to the London Wasps in 2012, he has become a key player for both the team and the England national team.

Police in Sydney are urging witnesses to come forward after a video of a middle-aged woman's rant against a Muslim woman on a train was published by Daily Mail Australia. The incident occurred on an Airport Line train around 1:40 pm on Wednesday, when the woman began berating the Muslim woman and her partner with Islamophobic comments and insults. Stacey Eden, a 23-year-old passenger who was sitting nearby, recorded the incident on her phone and stepped in to defend the couple. The police spokeswoman contacted Daily Mail Australia on Thursday and urged witnesses to come forward with any information. The video shows Eden firing back at the woman and telling her to 'have some respect' while the woman continues to insult the Muslim couple.

Ursula Ward, the mother of Odin Lloyd, is suing Aaron Hernandez for her son's wrongful death. Hernandez was found guilty of first-degree murder for killing Lloyd in 2013 and is facing a civil lawsuit filed by Ward. Ward wants to see Hernandez testify during the trial and has hired lawyers to represent her. Hernandez, a former New England Patriots player, was convicted and sentenced to life in prison without parole.

Britain has struck oil in the Falklands, escalating tensions with Argentina over ownership of the islands. Argentina has threatened to prosecute oil companies operating off the Falklands coast, claiming they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. The discovery, made by British firms in a remote field of the islands, could be worth billions of pounds and has brought fears of renewed conflict. Argentina has also accused Britain of aggression and circulated allegations of British espionage. Lord West of Spithead, a former First Sea Lord, warned that the find would lead to further claims by Argentina over the long-disputed territory in the South Atlantic.

A three-legged cat named Freeman was mauled to death by two dogs in a brutal attack captured on CCTV in Tarring, West Sussex. The attack lasted for 90 seconds and was so severe that the cat died in agony. A woman is seen collecting the dogs and leaving the cat to die. The cat's owner, Tracy Lynch, is devastated and unhappy that the dog owners didn't check on the cat's well-being. The police are investigating the case and the large dogs, possibly Dobermans, were collected by someone in a blue car. The cat was a popular figure in the neighbourhood and will be missed by the neighbours.

A Chinese woman has become an internet sensation for her close relationship with her pet pig, which she dresses, walks, and even sleeps with every day. The pig, named Five Flowers, weighs 187lbs and sleeping in the same bed with her owner, but the owner's dog is reportedly jealous. The woman works at a publishing company in Beijing, and her pictures with Five Flowers have generated a lot of attention online, with many netizens expressing support for her unusual pet.
